<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun3-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>FUN-3 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <statement><p>Find the equation for the line tangent 
          to <m>\vec{r}(t)=e^{2t}\hat{i}+e^t\hat{j}</m> at 
          <m>t=0</m>.Leave the answer in vector form.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the equation of the tangent line, you 
          need to compute the derivative of the vector-valued 
          function and evaluate it at the given point.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>Tangent line: <m>\lt 1+2t,1+t \gt</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First we need to find <m>\vec{r}(0)</m>: 
          <m>\vec{r}(0)=1\hat{i}+1\hat{j}</m>.</p><p>Next, we compute 
          the derivative: <m>\vec{r}^{\prime}(t)=2e^{2t}\hat{i}+e^t\hat{j}</m>.</p> 
          <p>Then we evaluate at <m>t=0</m>: <m>\vec{r}^{\prime}(0)=2\hat{i}+1\hat{j}</m>. 
          The tangent line is <m>\lt 1+2t,1+t \gt</m>.</p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>Find the distance traveled along the helix given by 
        <m>\vec{r}(t)=\lt 5\cos(2t),5\sin(2t),2t \gt</m> as 
        <m>t</m> varies from 0 to <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>.</p></statement>
      <hint><p>To find the distance traveled, you need to compute the 
        arc length integral over the interval in terms of <m>t</m>.</p></hint>
      <answer><p>Distance traveled: <m>3\pi\sqrt{26}</m> units</p></answer>
      <solution><p>To set up the arc length integral, we first 
          compute the derivative of <m>\vec{r}(t)</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\vec{r}^{\prime}(t)=\lt -10\sin(2t),10\cos(2t),2 \gt</m>.</p>
          <p>The magnitude of this vector is:</p>
          <p><m>|\vec{r}^{\prime}(t)|=\sqrt{100\sin^2(2t)+100\cos^2(2t)+4}=\sqrt{104}=2\sqrt{26}</m>.</p>
          <p>The arc length is then:</p><p><m>S=\int_0^{3\pi/2} 2\sqrt{26} dt</m></p>
          <p><m>S=2\sqrt{26}t | _0^{3\pi/2}=3\pi\sqrt{26}</m> units.</p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>A particle is moving along a curve in space with velocity (measured in m/s) of <m>\vec{v}(t)=\lt 2t,3t^2,4 \gt</m>.</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the position vector of the particle, <m>\vec{r}(t)</m>, if <m>\vec{r}(3)=\lt 2,-2,6 \gt</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the position vector, integrate the velocity vector and use the initial condition.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\vec{r}(t)=\lt t^2-7, t^3-29, 4t-6 \gt</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>Integrating the velocity vector:</p>
          <p><m>\vec{r}(t)=\lt \int 2t \, dt, \int 3t^2 \, dt, \int 4 \, dt \gt</m></p>
          <p><m>=\lt t^2, t^3, 4t \gt + \vec{c}</m>.</p>
          <p>Using the initial condition <m>\vec{r}(3)=\lt 2,-2,6 \gt</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\lt 9, 27, 12 \gt + \vec{c}=\lt 2,-2,6 \gt</m></p>
          <p><m>\vec{c}=\lt -7, -29, -6 \gt</m>.</p>
          <p>Therefore: <m>\vec{r}(t)=\lt t^2-7, t^3-29, 4t-6 \gt</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the unit tangent vector at <m>t=3</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The unit tangent vector is the derivative of the position vector, normalized.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\vec{T}(3)=\lt \frac{6\sqrt{781}}{781}, \frac{27\sqrt{781}}{781}, \frac{4\sqrt{781}}{781} \gt</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, we find the derivative of the position vector. But notice that <m>\vec{r}^{\prime}(t)=\vec{v}(t)</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\vec{v}(t)=\lt 2t,3t^2,4 \gt</m>.</p>
          <p>Then we evaluate at <m>t=3</m>:</p>
          <p><m>\vec{v}(3)=\lt 6,27,4 \gt</m>.</p>
          <p>The magnitude is:</p>
          <p><m>|\vec{v}(3)|=\sqrt{36+729+16}=\sqrt{781}</m>.</p>
          <p>The unit tangent vector is:</p>
          <p><m>\vec{T}(3)=\frac{\lt 6,27,4 \gt}{\sqrt{781}} = \lt \frac{6\sqrt{781}}{781}, \frac{27\sqrt{781}}{781}, \frac{4\sqrt{781}}{781} \gt</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
